d operated the IBT as a racketeering enterprise for decades, systematically violating the rights of members and furthering the interests of organized crime. On the eve of trial, the parties settled the case, and twenty years later, the trustees are still on the job. Breaking the Devil's Pact is an in-depth study of the U.S. v. IBT, beginning with Giuliani's lawsuit and the politics surrounding it, and continuing with an incisive analysis of the controversial nature of the ongoing trusteeship. James B. Jacobs and Kerry T. Cooperman address the larger question of the limits of legal reform in the American labor movement and the appropriate level of government involvement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aLabor unionsxCorrupt practicesxHistoryxUnited States. 0aLabor unionsxCorrupt practiceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMafia trialsxUnited States. 0aMafia trialszUnited States. 0aOrganized crime investigationxHistoryxUnited States. 0aOrganized crime investigationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRacketeeringxHistoryxUnited States. 0aRacketeeringzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh1 aCooperman, Kerry T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814743089.001.0001zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814743669zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814743669/original  a978-3-11-070644-4 New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA